		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Chanakya</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the Indian television series based on his life, see <a href="/wiki/Chanakya_(TV_series)" title="Chanakya (TV series)">Chanakya (TV series)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:261px;"><a href="/wiki/File:India_CG3.jpg" class="image" title="The court of Chandragupta Maurya, especially Chanakya, played an important part in the foundation and governance of the Maurya dynasty."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/India_CG3.jpg/259px-India_CG3.jpg" width="259" height="194" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:India_CG3.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The court of Chandragupta Maurya, especially Chanakya, played an important part in the foundation and governance of the <a href="/wiki/Maurya_dynasty" title="Maurya dynasty" class="mw-redirect">Maurya dynasty</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Chanakya</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: चाणक्य <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Cāṇakya</span></i>) (c. 350-283 BCE) was an adviser and a <a href="/wiki/Prime_minister" title="Prime minister">prime minister</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> to the first <a href="/wiki/Maurya_Empire" title="Maurya Empire">Maurya</a> Emperor <a href="/wiki/Chandragupta_Maurya" title="Chandragupta Maurya">Chandragupta</a> (c. 340-293 BCE), and architect of his rise to power. <b>Kautilya</b> and <b>Vishnugupta</b>, the names by which the ancient Indian political treatise called the <b><a href="/wiki/Artha%C5%9B%C4%81stra" title="Arthaśāstra" class="mw-redirect">Arthaśāstra</a></b> identifies its author, are traditionally identified with Chanakya.<sup id="cite_ref-Mabbett_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mabbett-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Chanakya has been considered as the pioneer of the field of <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>, preceding <a href="/wiki/Ibn_Khaldun" title="Ibn Khaldun">Ibn Khaldun</a> in writing about it by about a millennium and a half.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> He is known as "The <a href="/wiki/History_of_India" title="History of India">Indian</a> <a href="/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Machiavelli" title="Niccolò Machiavelli">Machiavelli</a>" in the Western world.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> Chanakya was a <a href="/wiki/Professor" title="Professor">professor</a> at <a href="/wiki/Taxila" title="Taxila">Takshashila University</a> and is widely believed to be responsible for the creation of <a href="/wiki/Mauryan_empire" title="Mauryan empire" class="mw-redirect">Mauryan empire</a>, the first of its kind on the Indian subcontinent.</p>
